). Carapace, tergites, metasoma and usually femur of pedipalps and legs black, tibia and tarsomeres of legs and fingers of pedipalps yellow. Patella of legs and pedipalps and pedipalp chela yellowish brown to brown. Sternite VII black, other sternites reddish brown to black with yellow median area present in posterior margin of sternites IV–VI. Telson reddish brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC036A0FFA16D5CFFF80DCEFE063CF7" blockId="9.[113,772,234,1763]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFFF80DCEFE693FB6" bold="true" box="[113,399,459,483]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Mesosoma and carapace</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13442A25FFA16D5CFE280DCEFDC23FB6" box="[417,548,459,483]" captionStart="Figures 11–19" captionStartId="6.[113,190,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[113,1474,248,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-87@6.[113,1474,248,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 11–19: Orthochirus hormozganensis sp. n. Figures 11–12, 15–18. Holotype male, carapace and tergites (11), sternopectinal region and sternites (12), and distal segments of right legs I–IV, retrolateral aspect (15–18 respectively). Figures 13–14, 19. Paratype female from type locality, carapace and tergites I–IV (13), sternopectinal region and sternites III–V (14), and distal segments of right leg III, retrolateral aspect (19)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4648540" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4648540/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Figs. 11–14</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13442A25FFA16D5CFDBA0DCEFD9D3FB6" box="[563,635,459,483]" captionStart="Figures 20–22" captionStartId="7.[113,190,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[113,1474,234,1947]" captionTargetId="figure-8@7.[113,1474,234,1973]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figures 20–22. Orthochirus hormozganensis sp. n., holotype male, carapace and tergites (20), sternopectinal region and sternites (21), and metasoma and telson dorsal (22) under UV light." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4648542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4648542/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">20–21</figureCitation>
). Mesosoma with a median carina, densely granulated. Carapace roughly granulated with smooth areas, mainly around medial eyes. Carination of carapace reduced to absent. The seventh sternite granulated, with four wide granulated carinae, the other sternites are granulated except smooth median area. Pectinal teeth number 
<quantity id="4C879B45FFA16D5CFE8D0E8EFE843CF6" box="[260,354,651,675]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.334" metricValueMax="5.588" metricValueMin="5.08" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" unit="in" value="21.0" valueMax="22.0" valueMin="20.0">20–22 in</quantity>
both sexes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC036A0FFA16D5CFFF80EAEFF333AD6" blockId="9.[113,772,234,1763]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFFF80EAEFE8A3C96" bold="true" box="[113,364,683,707]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Metasoma and telson</emphasis>
(Figs. 5–10, 22, 222). Metasoma I– II with 10 granulated carinae. Metasoma II–V lack lateral carinae, ventromedian carinae present on metasoma I–III, ventrolateral carinae present on all metasomal segments, dorsolateral carinae present on metasoma I–III and reduced to absent on metasoma IV–V. Ventral carinae of metasoma I– III consist of small granules irregularly forming two or three rows. All metasomal segments are granulated laterally, more in metasoma I–III; granulation absent on dorsal surfaces of all metasomal segments and ventral surfaces of segments IV–V. Segments IV–V ventrally and laterally are shallowly punctate; spaces among punctae are smooth. The entire metasoma and telson glabrous; short, thin setae might issue from some punctae. Telson shallowly punctate and lacks granules.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC036A0FFA16D5CFFF8088FFEAA3B96" blockId="9.[113,772,234,1763]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFFF8088FFF063AF7" bold="true" box="[113,224,1162,1186]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Pedipalps</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13442A25FFA16D5CFF79088EFE933AF6" box="[240,373,1163,1187]" captionStart="Figures 23–40" captionStartId="8.[115,192,1900,1922]" captionTargetBox="[134,1463,238,1861]" captionTargetId="figure-126@8.[115,1476,234,1862]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figures 23–40: Orthochirus hormozganensis sp. n., segments of pedipalps. Figures 23–31. Holotype male. Pedipalp chela, dorsal (23), external (24), and ventral (25) views. Pedipalp patella, dorsal (26), external (27), and ventral (28) views. Pedipalp femur and trochanter, dorsal (29), and ventral (30) views. Pedipalp chela, movable finger dentate margin (31). Figures 32–40. Paratype female from type locality. Pedipalp chela, dorsal (32), external (33), and ventral (34) views. Pedipalp patella, dorsal (35), external (36), and ventral (37) views. Pedipalp femur and trochanter, dorsal (38), internal (39), and ventral (40) views. The trichobothrial pattern is indicated in Figures 33–36, 38–39 (white circles)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4648544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4648544/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Figs. 23–40</figureCitation>
). The distance between trichobothria 
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFFF808AEFF983A96" box="[113,126,1195,1219]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">d</emphasis>
<subScript id="17FB34E5FFA16D5CFFF608BEFF613A9C" attach="left" box="[127,135,1211,1225]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">1</subScript>
and 
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFF3408AEFF2C3A96" box="[189,202,1195,1219]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">d</emphasis>
<subScript id="17FB34E5FFA16D5CFF4308BEFF343A9C" attach="left" box="[202,210,1211,1225]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">3</subScript>
on the femur of pedipalp approximately equals that between 
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFF5B08CEFF393AB6" box="[210,223,1227,1251]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">d</emphasis>
<subScript id="17FB34E5FFA16D5CFF6908DEFF0E3ABC" attach="left" box="[224,232,1243,1257]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">3</subScript>
and 
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFE9708CEFECD3AB6" box="[286,299,1227,1251]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">d</emphasis>
<subScript id="17FB34E5FFA16D5CFEA208DEFED53ABC" attach="left" box="[299,307,1243,1257]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">4</subScript>
; trichobothrium 
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFE6208CEFE113AB7" box="[491,503,1227,1250]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">e</emphasis>
<subScript id="17FB34E5FFA16D5CFE7F08DEFE183ABC" attach="left" box="[502,510,1243,1257]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">1</subScript>
is situated in level with 
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFFF808EEFF983B56" box="[113,126,1259,1283]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">d</emphasis>
<subScript id="17FB34E5FFA16D5CFFF608FEFF613B5C" attach="right" box="[127,135,1275,1289]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">4</subScript>
. Trichobothrium 
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFECB08EEFEA93B56" box="[322,335,1259,1283]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">d</emphasis>
<subScript id="17FB34E5FFA16D5CFED908FEFEBE3B5C" attach="left" box="[336,344,1275,1289]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">2</subScript>
on the dorsal surface of pedipalp femur absent or reduced. Femur of pedipalp with five granulated carinae. Patella with seven smooth reduced carinae; chela with smooth carinae, which might be discernible throughout the length of the fixed finger. The entire pedipalp only very sparsely hirsute. Movable fingers with 8 rows of denticles, 8–9 ID and 7–8 OD.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC036A0FFA16D5CFFF809CEFE153896" blockId="9.[113,772,234,1763]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFFF809CEFF403BB6" bold="true" box="[113,166,1483,1507]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Legs</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13442A25FFA16D5CFF3309CEFEA73BB7" box="[186,321,1482,1507]" captionStart="Figures 11–19" captionStartId="6.[113,190,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[113,1474,248,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-87@6.[113,1474,248,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 11–19: Orthochirus hormozganensis sp. n. Figures 11–12, 15–18. Holotype male, carapace and tergites (11), sternopectinal region and sternites (12), and distal segments of right legs I–IV, retrolateral aspect (15–18 respectively). Figures 13–14, 19. Paratype female from type locality, carapace and tergites I–IV (13), sternopectinal region and sternites III–V (14), and distal segments of right leg III, retrolateral aspect (19)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4648540" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4648540/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Figs. 15–19</figureCitation>
). Moderate tibial spurs present on third and fourth legs. Femur with four partly granulated carinae; patella with five rather smooth carinae; tibia smooth. Patella with only a few bristles. Tibia with bristles on the outer side of legs I–II. Tarsomere I of first to third legs with bristlecombs composed of 5–7 bristles, short in male and long in female; fourth legs lack bristlecombs. Tarsomeres I–II of all legs with two rather irregular rows of bristles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC036A0FFA16D5CFFF80ACEFE4E38B6" blockId="9.[113,772,234,1763]" box="[113,424,1739,1763]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFFF80ACEFEFE38B6" bold="true" box="[113,280,1739,1763]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Measurements</emphasis>
. See 
<tableCitation id="C6FD031BFFA16D5CFEDB0ACEFE4438B6" box="[338,418,1739,1763]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="4.[115,171,994,1015]" captionTargetId="graphics-530@4.[116,1474,234,972]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Table 1. Comparative measurements of Orthochirus hormozganensis sp. n. types. Abbreviations: length (L), width (W, in carapace it corresponds to posterior width), depth (D)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF006628FFAC6D51FFFA0FE7FE3B3A40" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" tableUuid="DF006628FFAC6D51FFFA0FE7FE3B3A40">Table 1</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C365652BFFA16D5CFFF80B0EFC793F37" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC036A0FFA16D5CFFF80B0EFC793F37" blockId="9.[113,771,1803,2019]" lastBlockId="9.[816,1474,235,354]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
AFFINITIES. The described features distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="4C7F4D23FFA16D5CFD600B0EFEC33916" authority="Kovařík &amp; Navidpour, 2020" authorityName="Kovařík &amp; Navidpour" authorityYear="2020" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Orthochirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hormozganensis" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFD600B0EFEC33916" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">O. hormozganensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23857C9FFA16D5CFEA70B2EFE883917" box="[302,366,1835,1859]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" rank="species">
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFEA70B2EFEAE3916" bold="true" box="[302,328,1835,1859]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">sp</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFED10B2EFE813916" bold="true" box="[344,359,1835,1859]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">n</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
from all other species of the genus. They are recounted in the key below. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7F4D23FFA16D5CFDA30B4EFCE53936" authority="Kovařík &amp; Navidpour, 2020" authorityName="Kovařík &amp; Navidpour" authorityYear="2020" box="[554,771,1867,1891]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Orthochirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hormozganensis" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFDA30B4EFCE53936" box="[554,771,1867,1891]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">O. hormozganensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23857C9FFA16D5CFFF80B6EFF5339D7" box="[113,181,1899,1923]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" rank="species">
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFFF80B6EFF6D39D6" bold="true" box="[113,139,1899,1923]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">sp</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFF160B6EFF4839D6" bold="true" box="[159,174,1899,1923]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">n</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C7F4D23FFA16D5CFED20B6EFD9B39D6" authority="Kovarik, 2004" authorityName="Kovarik" authorityYear="2004" box="[347,637,1899,1923]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Orthochirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varius">
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFED20B6EFE2139D7" box="[347,455,1899,1922]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">O. varius</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFEE4B51FFA16D5CFE5D0B6EFD9B39D6" author="KOVARIK" box="[468,637,1899,1923]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" pagination="1 - 33" refId="ref13512" refString="KOVARIK, F. 2004. Revision and taxonomic position of genera Afghanorthochirus Lourenco &amp; Vachon, Baloorthochirus Kovarik, Butheolus Simon, Nanobuthus Pocock, Orthochiroides Kovarik, Pakistanorthochirus Lourenco, and Asian Orthochirus Karsch, with descriptions of twelve new species (Scorpiones, Buthidae). Euscorpius, 16: 1 - 33." type="journal article" year="2004">Kovařík, 2004</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. These two species can be distinguished according to the metasoma morphology. In the key below, we used the difference in granulation of carinae. Another difference is in the granulation of the ventral surfaces on metasoma I–III, which are densely granulated in the male of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7F4D23FFA16D5CFB600D0EFA243F76" authority="Kovařík &amp; Navidpour, 2020" authorityName="Kovařík &amp; Navidpour" authorityYear="2020" box="[1257,1474,267,291]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Orthochirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hormozganensis" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFB600D0EFA243F76" box="[1257,1474,267,291]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">O. hormozganensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23857C9FFA16D5CFCB90D2EFC963F17" box="[816,880,299,323]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" rank="species">
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFCB90D2EFCAC3F16" bold="true" box="[816,842,299,323]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">sp</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFCD30D2EFC8F3F16" bold="true" box="[858,873,299,323]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">n</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
(Fig. 10) and rather smooth with several granules in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7F4D23FFA16D5CFCB90D4EFC7E3F37" authorityName="Kovarik" authorityYear="2004" box="[816,920,331,354]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Orthochirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varius">
<emphasis id="B90BEAB2FFA16D5CFCB90D4EFC7E3F37" box="[816,920,331,354]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">O. varius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
